<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="25" type="taxonomical notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Taxonomical notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Pontederia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pontederia sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Pontederia sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a poorly circumscribed taxon that is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. cordata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. cordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the shape of the blade of their petiolate leaves. However, it is molecularly more closely related to 
<taxonomicName family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. ovalis" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, having in common the anthocarp with sinuate ridges. The disjunctive distribution of 
<taxonomicName family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably related to misidentified specimens and/or the presence of cryptic species in what we currently accept as 
<taxonomicName family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">s.l.</emphasis>
Great variation in petiolate leaf shape can be observed throughout its distribution, especially in Brazil. We believe that 
<taxonomicName family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be properly studied, using different approaches than traditional taxonomy, in order to solve this issue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
